AUDIO: 'some spreadsheet edit log. A real version database. That\'s the whole core idea here. Get workflows but for tables. Now, let\'s pull back everything and see how all this actually works. At first,'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Dol feels familiar on purpose. You have commands like Dol status, diff, add, commit, branch, checkout. If you know Git, your brain already understands the shape of this entire workflow they\'re'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going for. Dolt is not tracking files. It\'s tracking relational tables. You can use it from the command line or you can run Dolt SQL Server. By doing that, you can now connect it using MySQL'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'compatible clients, OMS, BI tools or application code. So your app can treat Dol like a normal SQL database, but you get version control around the data. That\'s the important part. You\'re not'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'choosing between a real database and a Git workflow. You get both in the same place. Dol uses something called crawly tree. The easy version of probably tree here is a normal database uses treelike'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'structures to make reads and writes fast. Dol uses a treelike structure that is also good at versioning. So instead of copying the whole database every time you commit, Dol can share the parts that'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stayed the same and track the parts that actually changed. Now we\'re not just asking things like, hey, what\'s the current value? We can actually ask things like, what did this row look like before something happened? That\'s the big thing here cuz when something'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'breaks, we don\'t want to have to guess. You want to inspect the history. I can now review the diff. You can see the change and if needed, you can roll back. This is version control for structured data. Your branches, commits, diffs,'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'merges, histories for rows and columns. So, where does Dolt actually fit into the flow of things? Because this all sounds great, but this is where it might get confusing. You might hear git for'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data and you\'re probably thinking, okay, well look, we already have tools for that. Yes, we kind of do have tools for those, but they solve different problems. You can put CSVs and JSON files in Git that works when the data is'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tiny and simple. Git doesn\'t understand your schema. It doesn\'t know your primary key, and it\'s not going to enforce constraints. It can\'t run joins on your CSV unless you add more tools.'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, Git gives you version control, but it\'s not really for a database. Then there\'s DVC. DVC is great for ML workflows, especially large data sets and model artifacts, but it\'s not trying to be your live relational database.'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Yes, you have Lake FS that brings Gitlike ideas to object storage and data lakes. Very useful at lake scale, but again, that\'s an entirely different layer. It\'s it\'s not the same thing as'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saying branch the SQL table, change some rows, run a diff, and merge it back. Traditional databases also have history tools. Temporal tables, audit log, CDC, but most of them don\'t feel like a'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'normal workflow. They don\'t give you the clean loop, branch, change, diff, merge, roll back. I wouldn\'t blindly drop into every production system. That\'s not the point here. The point is this. If your'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work involves structured data that changes over time and those changes can actually break things, I think Dolt is worth trying. The first time it saves you from one silent bad data change, the'

